---
import HomeBase from "../../layouts/HomeBase.astro";
import SiteFooter from "../../components/sections/SiteFooter.astro";
import SiteHeader from "../../components/sections/SiteHeader.astro";
import home from "../../content/home.json";

const description = "How 22 Strong Foundation handles money, care, trust, and its provider relationship.";
---

<HomeBase title="How the money moves" description={description}>
  <div class="site site--about">
    <SiteHeader current="transparency" />

    <main id="main" class="about-page transparency-page">
      <section class="transparency-hero" aria-labelledby="transparency-title">
        <div class="transparency-hero__inner">
          <p class="eyebrow">Transparency</p>
          <h1 id="transparency-title">How the money moves</h1>
          <p class="lead">
            22 Strong Foundation is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit. We pay for recovery care when a
            veteran's or a young person's coverage runs out before recovery is finished. Because
            of how this organization started, we owe you a plain explanation of how it's built
            and where donations go.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="transparency-copy">
        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="where-started">
          <h2 id="where-started">Where we started</h2>
          <p>
            22 Strong grew out of Next Level Fitness & Wellness Center, a sports-medicine clinic
            in Newport Beach. Two of the people who lead the foundation, Dr. Vasili Gatsinaris
            and Travis Mayfield, co-own that clinic. Right now, the care we fund is provided
            there.
          </p>
          <p>
            That means your donation can pay for care at a clinic our founders have a financial
            stake in. You shouldn't have to dig for that fact, so we state it here and on the
            care pathway. The foundation's job stays narrow: it funds approved recovery care for
            people whose next appointment is at risk.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="what-money-funds">
          <h2 id="what-money-funds">What your donation pays for</h2>
          <p>
            22 Strong pays for hands-on recovery sessions when insurance runs out before
            recovery is finished. A session is listed at $190. No money passes through the
            person receiving care.
          </p>
          <ul class="transparency-list transparency-list--checks">
            <li>Funds are committed to approved recovery care. They are not general revenue for the clinic.</li>
            <li>The care recipient is never billed for a funded session.</li>
            <li>The foundation does not provide emergency care, diagnosis, insurance advice, or cash payments.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="funding-decision">
          <h2 id="funding-decision">How a funding decision gets made</h2>
          <p>
            A referral or request starts the process. 22 Strong checks whether there is a real
            gap: coverage has run out and the next appointment is otherwise out of reach. If the
            case fits the mission, donor funding covers the care so treatment can continue.
          </p>
          <p>
            Any decision involving Next Level is handled as a related-party decision. A 22
            Strong leader with a financial interest in the clinic has to disclose that interest
            and cannot approve a decision that would benefit them personally.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="provider-relationship">
          <h2 id="provider-relationship">Why care currently runs through Next Level</h2>
          <p>
            The foundation exists because Dr. Gatsinaris and Mr. Mayfield kept seeing the same
            problem inside the treatment room: a patient was improving, and the next appointment
            wasn't covered or affordable. 22 Strong was set up to pay for that next appointment.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today, all funded care runs through Next Level Fitness & Wellness Center in Newport
            Beach. If we add providers or change the session amount, this page will say so.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="transparency-section" aria-labelledby="records">
          <h2 id="records">What you can check or ask</h2>
          <ul class="transparency-list">
            <li>22 Strong Foundation is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit.</li>
            <li>EIN: 99-1232582.</li>
            <li>Questions about the provider relationship, funded care, or giving: <a href="/#contact">contact us</a>.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="transparency-legal">22 Strong Foundation. 501(c)(3). EIN 99-1232582. Donations are tax-deductible.</p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <section class="transparency-policy" aria-labelledby="policy-title">
        <div class="transparency-policy__inner">
          <p class="eyebrow">Conflict standard</p>
          <h2 id="policy-title">How we manage the Next Level relationship</h2>

          <p>
            The conflict, stated plainly: 22 Strong funds care at a clinic that two of its
            leaders co-own. It's named here so nobody reading this page has to guess how the
            model works.
          </p>

          <h3>What the foundation does and doesn't do</h3>
          <p>
            22 Strong is a funder of approved recovery care. It does not diagnose injuries or
            give insurance advice, and it never hands cash to individuals.
          </p>

          <h3>Who approves what</h3>
          <p>
            If a decision could benefit a director, officer, family member, or a business they
            own, that interest gets disclosed before the decision is made. Nobody approves a
            benefit to themselves or their own business.
          </p>

          <h3>What a donor can trace</h3>
          <p>
            Every funded session connects back to a referred person and the listed session
            amount, so you can see what your money paid for.
          </p>

          <h3>When this page changes</h3>
          <p>
            New providers, a new session amount, or added review steps get recorded here. The
            relationship should be visible before a donor has to ask.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <SiteFooter footer={home.footer} homeHrefPrefix="/" />
  </div>
</HomeBase>
